NAIROBI SHEEP DISEASE - TANZANIA
********************************
A ProMED-mail post
See Also
Rift Valley fever - Tanzania 980226204610
Date: Sun, 8 Mar 1998 18:27:22 -0600
From: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Source: OIE Report, 3 March 1998

Text of a fax received on 3 March 1998 from Dr J.N. Melewas, Director of
Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives, Dar es Salaam:
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: February 1998.
Estimated date of first infection: February 1998.
Location No. of outbreaks
several villages in Arusha and
Kilimanjaro regions (northern Tanzania) 14

Description of affected population: agro-pastoral livestock sector of
northern Tanzania - the Masai ecosystem. Three human cases were reported in
two villages.
Total number of animals in the outbreaks:
species Ovine 9 cases
Caprine 29 cases
Camel 1 case

Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: National Institute for Virology
(South Africa).
B. Diagnostic tests used: ELISA(1) (IgG).
Epidemiology:
A. Source of agent / origin of infection: carrier state in natural vectors.
B. Mode of spread: natural transmission by all stages of the brown ear tick
Rhipicephalus appendiculatus.
C. Other epidemiological details: effect of unusually heavy long rains (El
Nino) causing massive build up of vector ticks.
Control measures during reporting period: quarantine and movement control
inside the country; testing; control of arthropods.
(1) enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay.
